Ford GoBike Data Exploration¶

by (Asmaa Mostafa)¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶


This notebook explores a dataset containing information about Ford's GoBike program for San Francisco area from june 2017 to April 2019 .The dataset is available through https://s3.amazonaws.com/fordgobike-data/index.html

# Build Dataset file

path = "D:/Data_UdacityProject3/"
files = os.listdir(path)
bike_dataset = []
print ("Preparing the Dataset")
for file in files:
    #print(text_file)
    filename = path+file 
    print(filename)
    df = pd.read_csv(filename)
    bike_dataset.append(df)
bike_df = pd.concat(bike_dataset) 
alldatasetfile="D:/Data_UdacityProject3/alldataset.csv"
if os.path.isfile(alldatasetfile):
    print ("File exist")
else:
    print ("File not exist")
    bike_df.to_csv (r'D:/Data_UdacityProject3/alldataset.csv', index = False)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset consist of 3254325 rides data from june 2017 to April 2019 with 16 features ( duration_sec ,start_time ,end_time ,start_station_id ,start_station_name ,start_station_latitude ,start_station_longitude ,end_station_id ,end_station_name ,end_station_latitude ,end_station_longitude ,bike_id, user_type ,member_birth_year,member_gender and bike_share_for_all_trip)

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm mostly interested in figuring out the features (gender, age, user_type) of the riders and the duration of the trips.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I expect that days of the week have effection on rides duration as holidays have mush time compared to working days also months of the year affect on trip duration as weather tempreature affect on riders. I think age of the riders may also affect on trip duration .As well, subscriber users are expected to have more interest than customer users . The affect of the gender on trip is hardly to be expected .

# plot the distribution of trip durations.
duration_bins = np.arange(0, df_gobikeford['duration_sec'].max() + 100, 100)
plt.hist(data = df_gobikeford, x = 'duration_sec', bins = duration_bins)
plt.xlim(0, 3000);
plt.title('Average Duration of Bike Rides', fontsize = 12)
plt.xlabel('Duration in Seconds')
plt.ylabel('Number of Rides')
plt.show()

It's right-skewed distribution so we need to apply logarithmic transform to the data .

In [18]:
# Trip duration distribution in log scale
log_binsize = 0.1
bins = 10 ** np.arange(0, np.log10(df_gobikeford['duration_sec'].astype(float).max())+log_binsize, log_binsize)
ticks=([10,50,70,150,500,1000,2000,5000,10000,20000])
plt.figure(figsize=[12, 6])
ax=plt.hist(data = df_gobikeford, x = 'duration_sec', bins = bins)
plt.xscale('log')
labels = ['{}'.format(v) for v in ticks]
plt.xticks(ticks,labels)
plt.xlabel('Duration in Seconds')
plt.ylabel('Number of Rides')
plt.show()

After applying apply logarithmic transform it's clear that duriation falls in ( 200 - 2000) seconds range but the peak point = 500 second ~ 8 minute around.

locs, labels = plt.xticks()

    plt.text(loc, gender_number-8, pct_string, ha='center', color='b')

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

Trip durations have a large range of values with right-skewed distribution , so I explored the data using a log transform. After applying apply logarithmic transform it appeared as unimodal with peak point = 500 second ~ 8 minute around

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

I added new variables: day,month,year,hour, age from existing variabes. Only deal with age <= 100 to be more reliable as the max age 114 and I think it is wrong.

plt.pie([subscriber_duration/total_duration*100,customer_duration/total_duration*100] ,startangle=90,autopct='%1.1f%%',labels=['subscriber_duration','customer_duration']);
plt.axis('equal');
plt.title('Duration ratio of subscriber and customer users', fontsize = 12)
plt.show()

However customer users percentage are only 11.3% but they shared 23.3% from total trip durations and this considers high ratio compared to their ratio of total users.

Most of riders age falls between 20 and 40 years old and young users had long trip duration. Female and other users have longer trip duration than males. There is different usage behavior between subscribers and customers. Customers ride more on the weekends, although subscribers usage among a Monday-Friday mainly.For customers there are some stations like San Francisco Ferry Building (Harry Bridges Plaza) and The Embarcadero at Sansome St stations have more trips compared to others.Customer users had high trip duration ratio compared to their participation ratio </p>
